
                                            The inquiry will be led by a judge and will look into tax administration and revenue challenges at Sars.

                                         JOHANNESBURG - Finance Minister Malusi Gigaba says President Jacob Zuma has agreed to establish an inquiry into the South African Revenue Service (Sars). Gigaba says he approached President Zuma with the request and was given the green light. “It’s important for us to look at other ways that may need to be taken in order to improve the capacity of revenue service and support the work of revenue collection. There has been a number of issues raised about the capacity of the revenue service,” the minister said. The inquiry will be led by a judge and will look into tax administration and revenue challenges at Sars.